#chapter([Hierarchical and Recursive Constructions], label: <chap:hierarchical>)

This chapter takes the flat baseline of @chap:methodology and asks what happens when a proof too large for one machine is cut into independent pieces and stitched back together. The answer is a family of constructions, built one decision at a time, from the simplest and leakiest to one that gives the route away on no assumption at all, organized by two findings. The first is the _dualism_: decomposing a proof, unlike decomposing the problem beneath it, saves no work, so no hierarchical construction is ever cheaper than the flat proof it replaces. The second is the _frontier_ the family traces once it is mapped, on which low cost, full parallelism, and structural privacy cannot all be held at once. The chapter's goal is to build each construction soundly, read what it costs and what it leaks, and so chart that frontier.

Chapter 4 built a proof that works and does not scale. The flat circuit proves an entire tour in one piece, on one machine, and we watched it grow without bound: past a certain size, no single prover can hold it. This chapter asks what to do about that. We will not answer by optimizing the flat circuit further, because @sec:permcheck already showed that the permutation mechanism, the one part we are free to vary, moves the wall by a fraction of a percent. We answer by changing the shape of the proof itself.

The path we take is the one the chapter title gives away, but we are going to arrive at it rather than assume it. We start from the flat baseline and the most natural idea for scaling anything too big for one machine, and we follow that idea honestly: building it up, watching what it buys, and watching what it breaks. The breakage is the interesting part. Decomposing a proof turns out to behave nothing like decomposing the problem underneath it, and seeing why is the conceptual center of this thesis. Once we understand what decomposition does and does not give us, the rest of the chapter is a controlled walk through the designs it makes possible, from the simplest and leakiest to the one that gives nothing away.

#section([From One Prover to Many], label: <sec:dualism>)

Recall where Chapter 4 left the prover. The flat circuit encodes the whole statement, every node of the tour and every constraint on it, as one object, and that object grows with $N$: more gates, a longer witness to solve, more memory to hold all at once. The proof it produces stays small, by succinctness, but producing it does not. Everything on the prover's side scales up together, and it all lands on a single machine. Somewhere up the size axis that machine runs out of memory, and the proof simply cannot be made. This is not a constant we can shave. It is a wall, and the flat design walks straight into it.

We have met this shape of problem before, on the other side of the fence. In @sec:research-questions we recalled how an optimizer handles a tour too large to attack directly: it _decomposes_ the problem. It cuts the map into regions, solves each region on its own, and stitches the partial tours together at the end. The pieces are small enough to handle, and they can be worked on independently, even at the same time. Decomposition is the standard answer to "too big for one pass", and it is natural enough that the obvious move here is to try the same thing on the proof. If one circuit for the whole tour is too big, perhaps many small circuits, one per piece of the tour, will fit where the single large one did not.

Let us make the move concrete, because the details are where the trouble hides. The tour is an ordered list of $N$ nodes, and we cut it into $K$ contiguous segments of $M = N \/ K$ nodes each: the first $M$ nodes form the first segment, the next $M$ the second, and so on around the cycle. Each segment is a short piece of the route, a path from its first node to its last. We then give each segment its own proof: instead of one circuit reasoning about all $N$ nodes, we build $K$ smaller circuits, each reasoning about the $M$ nodes of a single segment. And this already answers the problem we started with. The wall was a matter of memory, a circuit that grew until no machine could hold it. A segment circuit is a fraction of that size, small enough to fit where the whole would not, so even a single machine, proving the segments one after another and never holding more than one at a time, can get through an instance that defeated the flat prover. Decomposition clears the wall on its own, before parallelism enters the picture at all.

Parallelism enters as a bonus, and it is worth being clear that it is a bonus and not the goal, because that is what guides how we cut. If we are going to decompose anyway, we may as well decompose _well_: into segments that are genuinely _independent_, non-overlapping pieces that each carry their own block of nodes and need nothing from any other to be proved. Independence does nothing for the memory problem, which the cut has already solved. What it buys is time. Independent proofs need not be made in sequence: given several machines they can be produced in parallel, and even on a single machine with cores to spare they can be produced concurrently. The wall falls either way; independence is what lets the same total work also finish sooner. So we cut for independence on purpose, with the speedup in mind, and that quiet choice will turn out to matter more than it looks.

But now look closely at what one of these smaller circuits is actually set to prove, because dividing the work has quietly changed the job. The flat circuit established three things about the whole tour, the three constraint groups of @sec:proof-anatomy. Hold each of them up against a single segment, and the same thing happens to all three: a local part survives, and a global part is lost. Take the permutation check. A segment can still confirm that its own $M$ nodes are distinct, but the real claim, that the cycle covers all of ${0, dots, N-1}$ exactly once, is a statement about every node at once, and a segment holding only $M$ of them cannot so much as state it, let alone prove it; it has no way of knowing which nodes the other segments carry. The edge-cost check splits the same way. A segment can prove that the edges between its own consecutive nodes are genuine, but the edges that join one segment to the next belong to no segment, and so go unchecked by all of them. The threshold splits too: each segment can total the cost of its own piece, but the true sum runs over all $N$ edges, the joins included, and no single segment can assemble it. Cutting the proof, then, did not simply make it smaller. Along every one of the three constraints it sheared off the global half and kept only the local one. What remains in each segment is real, but it is a fragment, and the part that made the fragments _one tour_ is gone.

And that loss is only half of the trouble. The independence we cut the segments to have, the very property that lets them be proved in parallel, works against us here too. Because no segment knows anything about any other, nothing inside the $K$ proofs ties them to one another, or even to the same problem. The separateness that lets them run on different machines just as easily lets them be about different tours: for all the proofs themselves attest, $K$ valid segment proofs could have come from $K$ unrelated instances. The property we wanted for speed leaves us nothing to hold the pieces together.

Decomposition, then, leaves us holding two gaps at once, opened from two directions: the global half of every constraint, lost in the cutting and living now in no segment; and the link between the pieces, which was never there to begin with, since independence is precisely the absence of such ties. Different as they are, the two gaps call for the same kind of answer: something positioned _above_ the segments, able to see across all of them at once, that can re-impose the global constraints the division threw away and stitch the independent pieces into a single statement. This is the upper layer the word _hierarchical_ has been promising all along, the segments below and, above them, a recombining layer we will call the _glue_. The glue is not an optional refinement added for polish. It is forced, and forced twice over, the moment we decompose.

Naming the glue is not building it, and this is where the comfortable part ends. We are now committed to constructing a layer that re-establishes, after the fact and from the outside, every global property the cut threw away, and ties the independent pieces to one instance while it is at it. Whether it can do that cheaply, cheaply enough to leave intact the savings decomposition seemed to promise, is the question the rest of this section turns on. We follow it from here.

Start with what the glue must actually do. It has to put back exactly what the cut took out, the global half of each of the three constraints. What it has to work with is what each segment could honestly attest and hand up: the set of nodes that segment covered, its two endpoints, and its partial cost. From those it must rebuild the three global claims. For the permutation, it has to check that the $K$ node-sets, laid side by side, contain every one of ${0, dots, N-1}$ exactly once, no node claimed by two segments and none missing. For the edges, it has to supply and verify the $K$ joins, the edges that run from the end of one segment to the start of the next, which no segment owned. And for the threshold, it has to add the $K$ partial costs and the $K$ join costs and test the total against $T$. Do all three, and the $K$ fragments are once again a single, sub-threshold tour.

Now count what that costs, because the count is the whole point. Two of the three are cheap. The joins are just $K$ more edges, and verifying them is $K$ more Merkle proofs of the kind we already have; and notice that the books balance exactly, the $N - K$ edges proved inside the segments plus the $K$ joins proved in the glue make $N$ edges in all, the same $N$ the flat circuit proved. Summing $2K$ costs against $T$ is cheaper still. The permutation is the expensive one. To confirm that the $K$ node-sets tile ${0, dots, N-1}$, the glue has to take all $N$ published node values together and check that they are a permutation of $0$ through $N-1$, which is the very same $O(N)$ check the flat circuit ran over its cycle. The glue, in other words, performs a full global permutation check of its own, on top of all the work the segments already did.

Step back and add the whole scheme up against the flat baseline. Each segment does its own $O(M)$ work, a local check over its $M$ nodes plus the Merkle proofs for its $M - 1$ internal edges; with $K$ segments that sums to $O(N)$, the same order as the flat proof's single pass. Splitting a cost that grows in proportion to $N$ into $K$ equal pieces and adding the pieces back up returns the same $N$: there was never anything to save there in the first place. And then, on top of that conserved work, the glue lays down its own $O(N)$ permutation check and its $K$ joins. So the hierarchical scheme does not do less total work than the flat proof. It does a little more — a few percent at the sizes that matter, and more than that at small $N$ or large $K$, where the glue's fixed costs have not yet been diluted away. The per-segment circuits looked like a saving only because each one was small; summed, they were never smaller, and the recombination on top is a genuine addition.

This is worth sitting with, because it is the exact opposite of what decomposition does for the optimizer, and the contrast is precise. When the solver of @sec:research-questions decomposes a tour, it _adds_ a constraint: it forces the route to respect the partition, to finish one region before moving to the next. Adding a constraint shrinks the space of tours the solver must search through, and a smaller space is a faster search. That is the entire source of its gain, paid for in solution quality, since the best partition-respecting tour may be worse than the true optimum. Decomposing the proof does the mirror image. It does not add a constraint; it _weakens_ one. The global requirement that all $N$ nodes form a single permutation is relaxed into something purely local, since no segment can see beyond its own $M$ nodes; and a check that cannot see across segments lets more through: nothing local stops two segments from claiming the same node, so the relaxed proof is simply unsound. The only repair is to put the global constraint back, in the glue, at the full price it would have cost in the flat circuit. The weakening bought nothing, because soundness forced us to undo it.

Underneath the mirror image is a single asymmetry, the one between finding a solution and checking one. The solver is _finding_: it faces a space of possible tours that grows faster than any polynomial, and decomposition is a tool for pruning that space, for cutting one enormous search into several smaller ones. The prover is _checking_: it is handed the answer already and only has to confirm it, which is cheap, and linear, with no search in it anywhere. Decomposition is a search-pruning trick, and the prover has no search to prune. Turned on a proof, the trick finds nothing to cut, and can only add the cost of stitching the pieces back together. The optimizer and the prover are not doing the same kind of work, and the move that speeds the first up cannot speed the second, because the thing it acts on is not there.

This is the first of the chapter's findings, and the one the rest of the chapter has to live within. Call it the _dualism_: decomposition adds a constraint to a search and weakens one in a proof, helping the first and taxing the second, one operation pulling opposite ways on the two problems. For our proof it means there is no algorithmic prize for decomposing, no size at which the hierarchical total slips below the flat one, a claim @sec:factorial later makes good on with measurements. The total work is conserved, and a little more than conserved once the glue is paid — by a margin that shrinks toward a couple of percent as $N$ grows, and widens at small $N$ or large $K$. _Total work is conserved_ is a refrain we will come back to.

So the gap from the start of the section does close: the glue can re-establish every global property the cut threw away. But it closes at a price that swallows the saving we imagined we were chasing, and that saving, it turns out, was never on the table. What decomposition genuinely delivers is just what the two axes at the start of the section showed: not less work, but the same work made portable, small enough per machine to clear the wall, and independent enough to run in parallel. Decomposition does not shrink the proof. It relocates it. Keeping that distinction in view is what holds the rest of this chapter honest.

#section([Building the Two Layers], label: <sec:two-layers>)

The previous section left us owing a layer we named but did not build: the glue, the recombiner that must re-impose the global constraints and tie the independent pieces to a single instance. This section builds it, and the segments beneath it, for the first time. We aim for the simplest thing that can work, and we build it under one discipline that will guide the rest of the chapter: _make it sound first, then make it private_. Each time a problem appears, we fix the verification, and only once the proof is correct do we ask what it gave away. The order matters. It lets us see the privacy costs for what they are, a separate layer of problems with their own separate fixes, instead of tangling them with plain correctness from the start. The first construction we reach will, as it happens, leak the partition outright. We build it anyway, make it sound, and face the leak squarely once it stands.

We also work from the top down. Rather than build a segment and hope it provides what the recombiner needs, we begin with the glue: we ask what it must check to call the pieces a single tour, hand it those values as public inputs, and get it working on the assumption that they are honestly supplied. That assumption then becomes the segments' job. Starting from the glue's demands is what tells us, precisely, what each segment has to prove, and a step later, what it is forced to reveal.

#subsection([The Glue], label: <sub:glue>)

The glue's task is the one @sec:dualism handed it: take the $K$ independent segment proofs and certify that together they describe one tour, under the threshold. Let us grant the glue, for now, that it can see whatever it needs from the segments as honest public inputs, and discover what that "whatever" is by asking what it has to check. Three global claims were lost in the cut, and the glue must rebuild each one.

The first is coverage: between them, the $K$ segments must visit every node exactly once. To check that, the glue needs the set of nodes each segment covered. Give it those as $K$ published lists, laid end to end into a single array of length $N$, and the check is short and surprisingly strong: sort the whole array and require that it reads $0, 1, dots, N-1$. If it does, the $K$ sets hold each of the $N$ nodes exactly once, so no node was claimed by two segments and none went missing. Remove the check and either failure is open: two segments could both take node $3$, or a node could quietly disappear, and what is left is not a tour. It is worth seeing how much this one sort does. It catches an overlap between two segments and a duplicate inside a single segment in the same pass, and because the values it pins down are exactly $0$ through $N - 1$, it forces every node into range as well. One $O(N)$ check delivers coverage, global distinctness, and range together. It is also the very same $O(N)$ permutation check the flat circuit ran over its cycle, returned now at the top of the construction: this is the recombination cost the dualism promised, finally with a face.

The second claim is connection: the $K$ paths must be linked end to start into one closed cycle, not left lying as separate pieces. Each link is an edge from one segment's last node to the next segment's first, $K$ of them in all, the last running from the final segment back to the first to close the loop. The glue needs the endpoints to know which nodes to connect, so we give it each segment's start and end. It then checks the $K$ join edges the way the flat circuit checked all of its edges: each cost bound to the committed root by a Merkle proof, its leaf index pinned to the join it stands for. Remove this and the pieces need not meet at all; a prover could submit $K$ disconnected fragments and call the collection a tour.

The third is the threshold itself, the claim the whole proof exists to make. The glue needs each segment's internal cost, so we give it the $K$ partial costs; it adds them to the $K$ join costs it has just verified and requires the total to be at most $T$. With every cost in hand, this is one sum and one comparison.

#[
  #set text(font: "Libertinus Sans")
  #figure(
    kind: "listing",
    supplement: "Listing",
    caption: [The glue circuit, the recombiner over $K$ segments. The segment proofs publish the arrays it reads. It checks coverage by sorting the concatenated node sets against the identity (a); verifies each of the $K$ boundary edges against the committed root by one Merkle proof, the same construction as @fig:flat-merkle (b); and sums every cost against the threshold (c). The cross-check of @sub:cross-check ties each public array to the segment that produced it. Boundary edge $i$ runs from one segment's end to the next segment's start, $ends[i] -> starts[(i+1) pmod K]$, the wrap-around closing the cycle.],
    pseudocode-list(hooks: 0.5em, booktabs: true, booktabs-stroke: 1pt)[
      + *circuit* #fn[glue]$(N, K, DEPTH)$ #h(1fr)
        + *public* $allsorted[rng(0, N-1)], med starts[rng(0, K-1)], med ends[rng(0, K-1)],$
        + #h(2.4em) $partialcosts[rng(0, K-1)], med T, med root$
        + *private* $boundarycosts[rng(0, K-1)],$
        + #h(2.4em) $siblings[rng(0, K dot DEPTH - 1)], med pathbits[rng(0, K dot DEPTH - 1)]$ #h(1fr) #lc[hint: $K$ boundary proofs]
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(a) coverage: the $K$ published node sets, concatenated, tile $0 .. N-1$]
        + $sorted arrow.l$ #fn[sort]$(allsorted)$ #h(1fr) #lc[constrained sort, as @fig:flat-sort]
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, N)$:
          + *require* $sorted[i] = i$
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(b) connection: one Merkle proof per boundary edge $ends[i] -> starts[(i+1) pmod K]$]
        + $total arrow.l 0$
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, K)$:
          - #lc[the proof must open this boundary edge's matrix cell]
          + $leafidx arrow.l 0$
          + *for* $d$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, DEPTH)$:
            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space leafidx arrow.l leafidx + 2^d$
          + *require* $leafidx = ends[i] dot N + starts[(i+1) pmod K]$
          - #lc[replay the hash up the path; the result must be the root]
          + $node arrow.l boundarycosts[i]$
          + *for* $d$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, DEPTH)$:
            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(siblings[i dot DEPTH + d], node)$
            + *else*: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(node, siblings[i dot DEPTH + d])$
          + *require* $node = root$
          + $total arrow.l total + boundarycosts[i]$
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(c) threshold]
        + *for* $i$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, K)$:
          + $total arrow.l total + partialcosts[i]$
        + *require* $total <= T$
    ]
  ) <fig:hier-glue>
]

So the glue works (@fig:hier-glue), and in working it has told us precisely what it needs from each segment: the segment's node set, its two endpoints, and its internal cost. Hand it honest versions of those and it decides correctly whether the pieces form a sub-threshold tour. But that one word, honest, is holding up the whole construction. Nothing we have built stops a prover from feeding the glue whatever arrays make its checks pass: a tidy node set that tiles $0$ through $N - 1$, endpoints and costs chosen to match, none of it attached to a single real segment. The glue only ever checks relations among its public inputs; it has no way of knowing whether those inputs describe anything the prover actually holds. The values are promises. Promises need backing, and backing them is the job of the segment proofs, and of one last cross-check we come to once the segments are built.

#subsection([The Segment], label: <sub:segment>)

The glue told us what it needs, so the segment is not a guess: it is exactly whatever proves those public values honest. The glue read three things off each segment, the node set, the two endpoints, and the partial cost, and took them on faith. The segment's job is to retire that faith. It must prove that the node set it published is really the set of nodes it visited, that its endpoints are really its first and last nodes, and that its partial cost is really the sum of its internal edges, which in turn it must show are real. A segment is just the proof of those facts about one $M$-node piece of the tour. Notice what is absent from the list: anything global. The segment never argues coverage, or distinctness across segments, or even, as we will see in a moment, range in the soundness sense, because the glue's one coverage sort already settled all three. The glue's appetite did the segments a favor: by demanding so strong a check at the top, it left them very little to prove.

Take the node set first. The segment holds its $M$ nodes privately, in the order it visits them, as #inline[cycle_segment], and it must convince the glue that the public list #inline[sorted_nodes] is that same set. It does exactly what the flat circuit did to check a permutation, and no more: it sorts its private nodes and binds the result, position by position, to the published list. That is all. It does not check that the nodes are distinct, because a duplicate would show up in #inline[sorted_nodes] and be caught upstairs, in the glue's coverage sweep. The segment proves only that what it published is what it visited; whether what it visited is a legal share of the nodes is the glue's question, not its own. Drop this binding and the link breaks the other way: the published list need not be the segment's real nodes at all, and the glue would be sorting a fiction.

There is one local check the segment does keep, and it is the single piece of range the glue's coverage does not spare us. The segment is about to address the cost matrix with its nodes, forming a Merkle leaf index from each consecutive pair, and that arithmetic has to be well-defined: a wildly out-of-range node could overflow the index, or land it in the unused padding of the tree, where the leaves are zero and a cheap edge could be forged. So the segment range-checks its own nodes, #inline[cycle_segment[i] < N], before it uses them. This is not the global range the flat circuit got for free from its permutation; it is a local guard on the segment's own arithmetic. The glue's coverage would in fact reject an out-of-range node anyway, the moment the published set failed to tile $0$ through $N - 1$, so range here is doubly ensured. The segment keeps the check not because the assembled proof would be unsound without it, but so that each segment proof is well-formed and meaningful on its own, before any glue exists to catch its mistakes.

The edges are the segment's real work. A piece of $M$ nodes has $M - 1$ internal edges, and for each the segment does just what the flat circuit did: it reconstructs the leaf index from the supplied path bits, checks it matches the cell for that very edge so that no proof for a cheaper leaf elsewhere in the tree can be smuggled in, and hashes the edge cost up to the committed root. It does not touch the edges that join it to its neighbors; those belong to no segment, and a segment cannot see where a neighbor begins, so the $K$ joins are left to the glue. As it verifies its internal edges the segment adds up their costs and binds the sum to the published #inline[partial_cost]. Without that binding a prover could publish a smaller number and help the glue's total slip under the threshold; with it, the partial cost the glue trusts is the real one.

Two small bindings finish the segment. Its first and last nodes are published as #inline[start_node] and #inline[end_node], because the glue needs them to know where the joins attach, and each is pinned to the actual end of the path. Leave the pins out and a prover could name endpoints the segment does not really have, and the glue would stitch its boundary edges onto nodes that are not there.

