            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space leafidx arrow.l leafidx + 2^d$
          + *require* $leafidx = cyclesegment[i] dot N + cyclesegment[i+1]$
          - #lc[replay the hash up the path; the result must be the root]
          + $node arrow.l edgecosts[i]$
          + *for* $d$ *in* #fn[range]$(0, DEPTH)$:
            + *if* $pathbits[i dot DEPTH + d]$: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(siblings[i dot DEPTH + d], node)$
            + *else*: $space node arrow.l$ #fn[H]$(node, siblings[i dot DEPTH + d])$
          + *require* $node = root$
          + $total arrow.l total + edgecosts[i]$
        - #hide("")
        - #lc[(e) the published cost is the true internal sum]
        + *require* $total = partialcost$
    ]
  ) <fig:hier-segment>
]

That is the segment (@fig:hier-segment), and it is a lean object, far leaner than the flat proof it descends from, precisely because the glue carries the global weight. It proves a handful of local facts and nothing more. Each segment is now sound about its own piece, and the glue is sound about how the pieces fit, but the two are still strangers: the glue checked public arrays, the segments proved facts about private witnesses, and nothing yet says the arrays the glue read are the values the segments proved. One step remains to close that gap, and it lives outside the circuits entirely. We come to it next. And the leak we set aside is still there, in plain view now: every segment has published, in the clear, the set of nodes it covers. The proof is becoming sound. It is not yet private, and by our discipline that is the right order: first we finish making it sound.

#subsection([Tying the Proofs Together], label: <sub:cross-check>)

We now have two sound halves that have never been introduced. Run the verifier and it checks each of the $K + 1$ proofs in turn, and each passes: every segment proof confirms that some real piece of a tour has the node set, endpoints, and cost it claims, and the glue proof confirms that some arrays of node sets, endpoints, and costs fit together into a sub-threshold tour. But verifying a proof certifies only that its _own_ public inputs satisfy its _own_ circuit. It says nothing at all about whether two proofs are talking about the same thing. The glue's arrays and the segments' published values are separate objects, sitting in separate proofs, and nothing built so far forces them to agree.

See how badly that can go. A prover runs $K$ perfectly honest segment proofs over real pieces of a route, except that two of the pieces happen to share a node, so the pieces do not form a partition at all. The segments do not object; checking coverage was never their job. Then the prover builds the glue proof over a _different_ set of arrays, ones it simply makes up: a clean node set that runs $0$ through $N - 1$, with endpoints and costs invented to connect and to come in under the threshold. The glue sorts its made-up array, finds it tiles the nodes, verifies its made-up joins, sums its made-up costs, and passes. Every one of the $K + 1$ proofs verifies. Yet the tour the glue certified has nothing to do with the pieces the segments proved; its coverage check was run on fiction. We would accept a "tour" that visits one node twice and skips another. The same gap lets a prover quote tiny partial costs in the glue to duck the threshold while the real segments cost far more, or name one matrix root in the glue and another in the segments. As long as the proofs are never compared to one another, each is free to live in its own world.

The fix is the simplest thing in the chapter, and it is the reason the segments published their values in the first place. The shared quantities are all sitting in the open, in the public inputs of the proofs, precisely so they can be lined up. So after verifying the $K + 1$ proofs, the verifier makes one more pass, outside any circuit, and checks by plain equality that the proofs agree where they overlap: the glue's $i$-th node-set chunk must equal segment $i$'s published node set, the glue's start and end for segment $i$ must equal that segment's endpoints, the glue's $i$-th partial cost must equal that segment's partial cost, and all $K + 1$ proofs must name the same root. No hashing, no field arithmetic, no extra circuit, just comparing numbers the proofs have already laid on the table. With those equalities checked, the glue's arrays _are_ the segments' values, and the glue's tour _is_ the tour the segments built.

It is worth being clear about what this cross-check is and is not, because leaning on a step outside the proofs can look like cheating. It is not. Verification has already bound each public value cryptographically to its proof; the equality checks only confirm that a value bound to one proof matches a value bound to another, and those are deterministic integer comparisons anyone can re-run, with no secret and no assumption. They add nothing to the cryptographic trust base. What they do add is a little trusted code: the binding between the proofs now lives partly in a verifier's script rather than entirely inside a circuit, so that script must be written correctly and becomes part of what a skeptic has to audit. That is a real cost, but a modest and conventional one, of exactly the kind that aggregation and rollup verifiers already carry.

With the cross-check in place the construction finally stands. The $K + 1$ separate proofs have become a single statement: a sound proof that a sub-threshold Hamiltonian cycle exists, cut into pieces that can be proved independently and in parallel, which was the whole point. But look at _how_ we bound the pieces, because two choices we made almost without noticing will set the agenda for the rest of the chapter. The stitch lives _outside_ the proofs, in the verifier's cross-check; and it works on _plaintext_, on values the segments had to publish in the clear so the verifier could compare them. Both were simply the most direct thing that worked, and both come at a price. Because the stitch is external, the verifier's work now grows with the number of segments: it runs $K + 1$ proofs and $K$ rounds of comparison where the flat verifier ran one proof and nothing else. And because the stitch is plaintext, the partition is now public, spread across the segments' node sets for anyone to read. The proof is sound. It is time to count what soundness cost us, and we begin with the partition we just gave away.

#section([Counting the Cost], label: <sec:counting-cost>)

The proof is sound, and the first thing to do with a sound proof is to read its public inputs the way an adversary would, because everything there is, by definition, given away. Lay them out. Each segment has published the sorted set of the nodes it covers, its two endpoints, and its partial cost; the glue has published the segments' cyclic order, through the starts and ends its boundary edges connect. Together these do not name the route outright, since the interior order within each segment stays private, but they hand the verifier the whole _partition_: which nodes are grouped together, in what order the groups are visited, where the route crosses from one group to the next, and what each group costs.

It is worth saying, before we measure the damage, why a _zero-knowledge_ proof gives any of this away at all. Zero-knowledge hides the prover's _witness_, the values it keeps private, and makes no promise whatever about the public inputs: those are not hidden but _declared_, the very statement the proof attests to. So the partition leaks here not because the proof system is weak but because we placed the partition among the public inputs ourselves. The proof faithfully hides everything we made witness and faithfully exposes everything we made public; in this chapter privacy is nothing more, and nothing less, than which side of that line each value falls on. And because the proof system's zero-knowledge is the same in every construction we will build, it is never what tells two of them apart — the privacy differences ahead are entirely differences in where we drew that line.

To see how much that is, count what the verifier cannot pin down before and after. Before, with only the flat proof's promise that some valid cycle exists, the route is one of all the Hamiltonian cycles on $N$ nodes, a space of about $(N-1)! \/ 2$ of them, enormous for any real $N$. After these disclosures, the only freedom left is the order of the interior nodes inside each segment: a segment of $M$ nodes has its two ends fixed and its middle $M - 2$ free, so $(M-2)!$ arrangements, and at most $((M-2)!)^K$ across all $K$ segments. The collapse is severe. Take the smallest interesting case, $N = 8$ split into $K = 2$ segments of $M = 4$. Before, the route is one of $7! \/ 2 = 2520$ cycles. After, each segment fixes its two endpoints and is free only to shuffle its two interior nodes, $2! = 2$ ways, so the whole tour is one of at most $2 times 2 = 4$ possibilities, and the published partial costs can cut even that. The verifier has gone from a couple of thousand routes to a literal handful, and could simply try them against the cost matrix to recover the exact one. The partition did not narrow the search; it very nearly ended it.

Numbers aside, the disclosure is exactly the kind the scenario in @sec:motivation set out to prevent. The carrier wanted to prove her route came in under budget without revealing the route, and the partition gives away most of the route's shape. The node sets reveal which stops are served together, the territory carved into regions. The endpoints reveal where one region hands off to the next. The partial costs reveal which regions are cheap and which costly. The verifier never sees the exact order of stops inside a region, but it learns the structure of the operation, and at small instances, as we just saw, very nearly the route itself. This is real disclosure, not a rounding error.

None of it is a flaw in the construction; it is the construction working exactly as built. Our construction hides the interior order of each segment and discloses everything else, because everything else had to be public for the verifier's cross-check to compare. We knew, when we chose to stitch externally on plaintext, that this was coming, and by our discipline we built it sound first and looked second. Now we are looking.

It is worth stepping all the way back, because the journey through this section has a shape worth holding onto. We came into the chapter with a single problem, the wall, and decomposition solved it cleanly. But solving it raised a harder problem in its place, holding the independent pieces together as one tour, and answering that forced a chain of machinery: a glue to restore the global checks, a cross-check to bind the proofs to one another, and a set of values published in the clear so the binding could happen at all. We took the simplest sound route through each of those steps, and the bill came due all at once, in privacy. The simplest hierarchical proof we could build gives away nearly everything the flat proof kept secret; in effect we have traded our zero-knowledge for our parallelism, and that is not a trade we are willing to keep.

The detour was not wasted, though. We have a construction that works, and we understand, piece by piece, why each part of it is there and what it costs, which is exactly the ground the rest of the chapter is built on. From here we stop taking the simplest road and start improving on purpose: one problem at a time, each fix reusing the pieces we already have. And the first move is to stop seeing the costs as a scattering of separate complaints and recognize them as one cost wearing several faces, each of which, as it turns out, yields to a different remedy. We name that cost next.

#section([The Stitching Tax], label: <sec:stitching-tax>)

The cost has a name: the _stitching tax_. The dualism of @sec:dualism was a statement about the prover's total work, and its verdict was that decomposition saves none of it. The stitching tax is a separate bill, charged somewhere else: not on the prover's gate count but on the verifier's effort and on what the proof gives away. It is the price of taking $K$ proofs made independently and stitching them back into one statement a verifier will trust, and we have now met it in full, in three places. The point worth making is that they are not three taxes but one, charged three ways. The first is the _leak_ we just counted: the values the pieces share, their node sets, endpoints, and costs, had to be made public, and public values are public. The second showed up as we built the cross-check: the verifier no longer checks one proof but $K + 1$, and then runs $K$ rounds of comparison on top, so its work grows with the number of segments where the flat verifier's stayed flat. The third is the _bookkeeping_ itself: that comparison lives outside the proofs, in trusted verifier code, a small extra surface to write and to audit that the flat proof never needed.

They are one tax because they have one source. Independent proofs cannot speak to one another; the only way they can be related at all is through values they each expose in public, so independence forces a _shared public surface_, the node sets and endpoints and costs that the segments and the glue hold in common. That surface is the tax. It is what leaks, because it is public. It is what the verifier must check proof by proof and then reconcile, because it is spread across $K + 1$ proofs. And it is what the external bookkeeping exists to police. The three faces are not independent problems with three independent fixes; they are one surface seen from three sides, and anything that changes the surface moves all three at once.

How hard the surface bites is not fixed, though, and this is the part that organizes everything ahead. It is set by two decisions, and we made both almost in passing, when we reached for the simplest thing that worked. The first is _where_ the stitch is enforced. We put it outside the proofs, in the verifier's cross-check; it could instead live inside a proof, if some circuit verified the segments and re-ran the glue's logic on them directly, in which case the verifier would be back to checking a single proof and the external bookkeeping would disappear. The second is _what_ the shared values are made of. We used plaintext, the raw node sets and costs laid bare; they could instead be wrapped in commitments, so the verifier compares opaque blobs that reveal nothing, or be removed from the public surface altogether and handed to a circuit as private witness. Two decisions, each with a few settings, and between them they fix how hard each face of the tax presses.

Seen this way, what we built is not _the_ hierarchical proof but one corner of a small space of them. Call it plain-sort: the stitch enforced _externally_, the shared values left as _plaintext_. It is the corner that pays every face of the tax in full, which is exactly why it was the right place to begin, the clearest one to take apart. Each construction in the rest of the chapter is a move away from this corner along one of the two decisions, changing where the stitch lives or what it is made of, easing one face of the tax while we hold the others still, so that we can read off what each move costs and what it buys on its own. That discipline, one change at a time, is what keeps the comparisons honest, and it is the same discipline that ran through @sec:permcheck: never let two things vary at once.

There is also, before we touch either decision, a cruder lever to try first. Each segment publishes the entire sorted list of its $M$ nodes, a surface that grows with the size of the segment. If a segment could instead publish a short _fingerprint_ of its node set, one value that stands in for the whole list, the shared surface would shrink from $M$ numbers to one, and a smaller surface is at once less to leak and less for the verifier to reconcile. Whether such a fingerprint exists, what it costs to compute and to check, and what it still gives away once published, is where we turn next.

#section([The Fingerprint Lever], label: <sec:lever>)

@sec:stitching-tax left us wanting a fingerprint: a single value a segment could publish in place of its whole node list, to shrink the shared surface from $M$ numbers to one. We do not have to invent it, because we built it already and set it aside. The grand product of @sec:permcheck was the permutation mechanism that compressed an entire multiset into one field element. We met it there as the odd one out, more elaborate than the sort and probabilistic where the others were exact, and at the flat level it bought nothing, since a flat proof's public surface was a single root with no partition to compress. We carried it forward anyway, and said plainly that we had only loaded a gun. The fingerprint we now want is that one field element, and decomposition is the target the gun was loaded for. This is where it fires.

#subsection([The Fingerprint], label: <sub:fingerprint>)

Recall the mechanism (@sub:grand-product). To test whether a list of values is some target multiset, you fold the values into a product, $product (X + v)$ for a challenge $X$, and compare it against the same product over the target; the two agree at a random $X$ exactly when the multisets match. What matters here is the shape of that product: it is one field element, and it stands in for the whole multiset no matter how many values went into it. That is the fingerprint we were after. So let each segment fold its own nodes into one, $P_i = product_v (X + v)$ taken over its $M$ nodes, and publish that single value in place of its sorted list.

The glue's coverage check changes character completely. Where plain-sort concatenated the $K$ published lists and sorted all $N$ values, the glue now multiplies the $K$ published products into one, $P_1 dot P_2 dots.c dot P_K$, which, because a product over a union is the product of the products, is the grand product over every segment node at once. It compares that against the product over the target set ${0, dots, N-1}$, and if the two agree, the segments' nodes are exactly $0$ through $N - 1$, each once. Coverage, established by multiplying $K$ numbers and checking them against one target.

The win is in the surface, exactly where @sec:stitching-tax said to look. Each segment's public contribution has dropped from a list of $M$ nodes to a single field element, $O(M)$ down to $O(1)$, and the verifier's cross-check shrinks with it: where it once lined up $M$ published nodes per segment against the glue's copy, it now lines up one. The glue's own coverage work changes too, though here the story is subtler than a clean win. The glue must still form the target product over all $N$ values of ${0, dots, N-1}$, which is $N$ multiplications, so its coverage is still $O(N)$, no shorter than before. But it is $O(N)$ of a far cheaper kind: straight-line field multiplications, with none of the dynamic, prover-chosen memory the sort dragged in (@sec:witness-inversion). The expensive sort is gone, and what replaces it is cheap arithmetic of the same length. The surface shrank; the glue's coverage got cheaper, if not shorter.

And there is a gain the surface accounting misses, one the chapter has chased since @sec:dualism: the grand product spreads the permutation work out. In plain-sort the whole coverage argument sat in the glue, which sorted all $N$ nodes in a single serial pass while the segments contributed nothing to it. The grand product breaks that pass apart. Each segment folds its own $M$ nodes into its product on its own machine, in parallel with the rest, so the work of running over the prover's nodes is now shared across the $K$ segments instead of piled on the recombiner. The glue still forms its target and combines the $K$ results, but the part of the check that scales with the prover's data has joined the segments in running side by side. The parallelism @sec:dualism prized for the proofs themselves now reaches into the permutation argument too, and the serial sort that was the recombiner's heaviest task is simply gone.

This looks almost free, and it is not. We have waved past the one thing the grand product cannot do without, the challenge $X$, and pinning it down across $K$ separate proofs is a real construction, not a formality. That, and the soundness it costs, and the question of what the fingerprint still gives away, are next.

#subsection([Binding the Challenge], label: <sub:challenge-binding>)

We have used $X$ as if it were simply handed to us, and where it comes from is the whole of the matter. Recall the danger @sub:grand-product guarded against. The grand product compares two multisets by comparing two polynomials at a single point $X$, and by Schwartz--Zippel a match at one point convinces only when the point was not picked to fit a wrong multiset. State the threat carefully, because it is easy to state it wrongly. It is not that the prover _knows_ $X$; in our scheme the prover knows $X$ perfectly well, since it is the prover that computes it. The threat is that the prover could _choose_ $X$, or know what it would be _before_ the tour is fixed, and then tailor a bogus product to that value. Fiat--Shamir removes exactly that freedom, by reversing the order of dependence. The tour is fixed first; only then is the challenge determined, as $X = H(c)$ with $c$ computed from the tour itself. The arrow runs one way, from tour to challenge, never back. Change the tour and the challenge changes with it. So a cheater cannot fix a wrong product and then go shopping for an $X$ that excuses it: the product and the point it is tested at are pinned to the very same nodes, and touching one moves the other. That single dependency, tour to challenge and not the reverse, is what makes the check sound.

At the flat level this was one hash chain over one cycle, run inside the single circuit that held every node: $h_0 = 0$, then $h_(j+1) = H([h_j, "node"_j])$ folded across all $N$ entries to a terminal $c = h_N$, and $X = H(c)$. Decomposition takes that circuit away. No segment sees more than its own $M$ nodes, and the glue sees no nodes at all, only the products and endpoints the segments published. The data the challenge must depend on is now spread across $K + 1$ separate proofs, and the chain that binds it has to be rebuilt across them without ever gathering the nodes in one place again.

It must depend on _all_ of the nodes, and it pays to see concretely what goes wrong if it does not. Suppose we economized and built the challenge from one segment's nodes alone, say the first. The prover proves that segment honestly, and in doing so it learns the exact $X$ that segment forces. From that moment $X$ is a known constant. Recall what the glue's check actually is: $product_i P_i = product_(j=0)^(N-1)(X + j)$, an equation in the published products. With $X$ fixed and known, the prover is free to settle the remaining segments _after_ the fact, and that is exactly the case Schwartz--Zippel does not cover. Its guarantee, that a wrong multiset passes at a random point only with vanishing probability, assumes the multiset was chosen before the point was drawn; choose it after seeing $X$ and the guarantee is void. The prover may then hunt for node values for the other segments that balance the equation at that one $X$, with no bound of probability standing in the way. This is the root-hunting attack of @sub:grand-product, reopened for every segment after the first, and one honest segment would buy the prover a free run at the other $K - 1$. The only defense is to fold every node into the challenge, so that no part of the tour can be settled while any other part is still open.

So we keep the flat chain and cut it at the segment boundaries. The chain is iterative: each step's output is the next step's input, so its value at any boundary is a complete summary of everything hashed up to that point, and a sound place to resume from. We expose that value at each cut. Every segment carries two public anchors, $h_"in"$, the chain's state as the segment begins, and $h_"out"$, its state as the segment ends. The prover, who holds the whole tour, runs the entire chain once in the clear and reads off these boundary values. Each segment is then handed its own $h_"in"$ as a public input, folds its $M$ nodes onto it in visit order, $h <- H([h, "node"])$, and must arrive at the $h_"out"$ it was given. That is one segment certifying its own stretch of the chain: from the state claimed at its left edge, its nodes really do carry the chain to the state claimed at its right edge, and to no other.

The glue makes the $K$ stretches into one chain, and it does so without hashing a single node. It checks three kinds of equality. First the start: the first segment has no predecessor, so its $h_"in"$ is fixed to the constant $0$, which is the flat chain's own starting value and denies the prover any freedom to begin the chain wherever it likes. Then the seams: each segment's $h_"in"$ must equal the previous segment's $h_"out"$, so that segment $i + 1$ resumes at exactly the state segment $i$ left off. Finally the close: the last segment's $h_"out"$ is named $c$, the terminal of the whole chain. Because the chain is iterative, these equalities are enough. If each stretch is honest about its own two boundaries, and each boundary matches its neighbour, then the $K$ stretches laid end to end _are_ the one flat chain over all $N$ nodes, in order, from $0$ to $c$. The glue has certified that for the price of $K$ equality checks and no hashing at all.

Pause on this, because it is the same gift the products gave, reaching one layer deeper. The challenge in the flat circuit was $N$ sequential hashes, one unbroken computation that nothing could share. Here that computation splits into $K$ pieces of $M$ hashes, one per segment, checked independently. The published anchors break the dependency: because each segment's entry state is given rather than waited for, the segments need not be proved in any order, and the $N$ hash constraints that derive the challenge distribute across them exactly as the per-segment products did. For the chain the glue keeps nothing: it checks that the stretches meet and hashes not a single node. The coverage product distributes almost as cleanly, save for the one residue we already met, the target product over the fixed set ${0, dots, N-1}$: that belongs to no segment, so the glue must still form it once, the $O(N)$ straight-line pass that replaced the sort. Either way, the part that runs over the prover's _own_ nodes has left the recombiner for the segments, and the serial sort that was plain-sort's heaviest glue task is gone.

It is worth being exact about what a single segment proves about the challenge, because the segment trusts the very value the challenge is built from. It is handed $c$ as a public input and does not check it: a segment cannot see the whole chain, so it has no way to know whether the $c$ it was given is the true terminal or a number the prover invented. What it checks is the one link within its reach, that the $X$ it was handed equals $H(c)$ for that $c$. Its guarantee is therefore conditional, and deliberately so: _if_ this $c$ is the real terminal, _then_ this $X$ is the honest challenge over the whole tour. The segment cannot make $c$ real on its own, and it does not try.

That is the glue's job, together with the cross-check, and it is the same promise-then-back move as @sub:cross-check. The stitching of the previous paragraph is what carries it out. The cross-check first ties the glue's copy of every anchor to the segment that produced it, so the glue is stitching real chain states and not invented ones; and the glue's three equalities, start at $0$, seam to matching seam, close at $c$, then pin $c$ as the one terminal of the one chain that runs from $0$ through every segment's real nodes, in order. The prover never chooses $c$. It falls out, fully determined, the moment the stretches and the seams hold. And now the relay closes. The nodes fix $c$ through the chain; $c$ fixes $X = H(c)$; and the $c$ each segment trusted on faith turns out to be exactly the $c$ the glue has nailed down. $X = H(c)$ is what makes $X$ honest, but it earns its meaning only because $c$ has been pinned to the nodes first: a hash of a value the prover could forge would protect nothing. The chain and the hash are one relay, not two separate checks.

Two notes on where these checks live, since both could in principle live elsewhere. The first is that $X = H(c)$ is recomputed _inside_ the circuits, in every segment and again in the glue, and not only by the verifier. The verifier could perfectly well recompute $H(c)$ in its own code, since it holds both $c$ and $X$ in the clear; this is defense in depth, not a soundness necessity. In fact $X$ need not be a public value at all: each circuit could derive it from $c$ internally and never expose it, since $c$ is already public and fully determines it. We carry $X$ explicitly only so the cross-check can confirm all $K + 1$ proofs share one challenge and the glue can consume it directly — publishing it gives an adversary nothing it could not already compute from $c$. Binding it in-circuit means the verifier's only off-circuit task is comparing numbers for equality, never reproducing a hash, and it means every proof certifies its own challenge, so that no single proof would accept a hand-picked $X$ even if the cross-check were skipped or written wrong. We repeat it in the glue as well as the segments because the partition check lives in the glue, so the glue's $X$ is the one soundness ultimately turns on. The second note is that the cross-check is still needed alongside all of this, and for a different reason. The in-circuit derivation makes each proof's challenge _honest_, tied to its own terminal; the cross-check makes the $K + 1$ challenges _the same_, one shared $c$ and one shared $X$ across every proof. A dishonest but shared challenge and an honest but per-proof one each break the construction in their own way, so honesty and agreement are both required, and they are checked in different places.

@fig:hier-segment-product and @fig:hier-glue-product set the two circuits down in full: the segment that publishes the fingerprint, and the glue that checks the partition through it.

