#subsection([The Surface Vanishes], label: <sub:perfect-hiding>)

The construction is sound (@fig:recursion-outer). Read its public surface now, the way @sub:product-leak and @sub:what-hides read the ones before it, as an adversary would, and there is almost nothing to read. The outer proof publishes two values. The Merkle root, which commits the cost matrix and which the flat proof published too; and the threshold $T$, which the statement is _about_ and is public by its nature. That is the entire surface. Every per-segment value plain-product laid in the clear, the $K$ products, the $2 K$ chain anchors, the endpoints, the partial costs, the terminal $c$, the challenge $X$, is now witness inside the outer proof, seen by the circuit and the prover and by no one else. The surface is the flat proof's surface, value for value: $(root, T)$ and nothing more.

So read what _kind_ of hiding this is, because it is not the kind @sec:committed bought. Committed hid the partition behind a _computational_ wall: its $K$ commitments sat on the surface, and their secrecy rested on Poseidon2 behaving as a random oracle and on a blinding $r$ staying secret. We called it one assumption below flat. Recursion is not one assumption below flat. It hides the partition the way flat does, by the partition not being on the surface at all. There is no commitment to break, no oracle to model, no blinding to guard: the values are not concealed behind a hardness assumption, they are simply _absent_, and what is not on the surface cannot be read off it by any computation whatever. The hiding is _structural_. That is not quite the same as resting on no assumption at all, and the difference is worth being exact about. Recursion still leans, exactly as flat does, on the one thing every proof in this thesis leans on: that the single proof reveals nothing of its own witness. And as with flat, that hiding is _from the verifier_, not from the prover: the party who assembles the outer proof consumes the $K$ segment proofs and sees their values in the clear, just as flat's prover knows its own cycle; what the final verifier, the recipient of the outer proof, learns is only $root$ and $T$. What recursion does _not_ do is add anything on top of that. Committed had to assume Poseidon is a random oracle in order to hide values it placed on the surface; recursion places nothing there, and so asks for nothing flat does not already ask. Its partition-secrecy rests on no assumption that flat's does not. This is the privacy endpoint the chapter has been climbing toward, and it stands strictly above committed, level with flat.

Walk the two things committed still gave away, and watch what becomes of each. The first was the segment count. Committed published $K$ commitments, so counting them told the verifier $K$, the number of pieces the tour was cut into. Recursion lays no per-segment array on the surface, so there is nothing there to count. $K$ does not disappear altogether: like $N$ in the flat circuit, it is fixed in the outer circuit and so encoded in the verification key a verifier must hold to check the proof at all. But that is the standing $N$ has always had, a public parameter of the statement rather than a value read off the proof. Committed disclosed $K$ twice over, once in its key and again in the $K$ commitments on its surface; recursion discloses it only the first way, the way every problem's size is disclosed, and never lays it on the surface to be counted. The second thing committed gave away was the challenge. Committed-product still published its $X$, the whole-cycle fingerprint that sat one level above the partition, the residue @sub:equal-privacy had to qualify its finding around. Here $X$ is witness like everything else, and that residue is gone outright. So of committed's two caveats, one shrinks to the bare circuit parameter every proof carries, and the other disappears completely.

This is the moment to collect a debt @sub:product-leak promised. The leak there marked out two independent moves: change _what_ the shared values are made of, or change _where_ the stitch lives. @sec:committed made the first, wrapping the values in commitments to hide them. Recursion makes the second, and it makes it so completely that the first stops mattering. Look at what the outer circuit verifies: plain-product segment proofs, whose nine values cross in the clear, uncommitted, plaintext. The inner does nothing to hide them. The outer hides them anyway, by taking them as witness. Committing the inner would be pure redundancy, hiding behind an assumption values the witness move already hides at no assumption. The secrecy @sec:committed paid a commitment and a random-oracle wall to obtain, recursion takes from the _where_ alone, and takes in the stronger, structural form. Moving the stitch inside did not improve on committing the surface. It made committing the surface unnecessary.

And privacy was only one face of the stitching tax. The other two, which @sec:committed left standing because they came from the _where_ it would not touch, close here in the same move. The verifier no longer checks $K + 1$ proofs and then runs $K$ rounds of comparison; it checks _one_ proof, the outer one, and Chapter 6 will show that check is as cheap as verifying any single proof. The external bookkeeping is gone with the cross-check that needed it: no trusted script outside the circuit, nothing to reconcile, because the one proof reconciles itself. All three faces of the tax, the leak, the $O(K)$ verifier, and the bookkeeping, close at once, because all three traced to the one source @sec:committed named, the stitch living outside, and we have moved it inside.

Structural hiding and a single verifier, bought by one move. The result is strong enough to raise two questions, and the section owes both. Why is the inner a plain-product proof and not one of the other constructions the chapter built, or a committed one? And what does the move cost, given that nothing this chapter has done has come for free? The first has an answer we promised back in @sub:weighing and can now make good on; the second is the price of that hiding, and it is the steepest the chapter pays. We take them in that order.

#subsection([The Forced Inner], label: <sub:forced-inner>)

Back in @sub:weighing we made a promise and deferred its proof. Plain-product, we said, leaking and plaintext as it was, earned its place in the chapter for one reason that had nothing to do with privacy: it was the substrate recursion would be built on, because the recursive verifier's cost turns on the inner proof's public surface, and plain-product's surface is the smallest there is. We can now measure that claim and make it good.

Why the inner's surface sets the outer's cost is plain from how the verification gadget works. To verify an inner proof, the gadget must absorb each of that proof's public inputs and bind it to the proof, in-circuit, a block of constraints per value. The more values the inner publishes, the more the gadget has to absorb, and the larger the outer circuit grows. So the outer's cost to verify one segment is set, in its dominant part, by how many public inputs that segment carries. Plain-product carries nine, whatever the segment's size: one product, two anchors, two endpoints, a cost, and the shared $c$ and $X$. Nine at $M = 24$, nine at $M = 1000$. The measurement follows exactly: verifying one plain-product segment inside the outer costs the same gate count, _to the gate_, whether the segment holds twenty-four nodes or a thousand. The cost is flat in $M$. Chapter 6 reports the number; what matters here is that it does not move.

Now swap the inner for plain-sort, and the cost stops being flat. A sort segment publishes its sorted node list, an $O(M)$ surface that grows with the segment: $M$ public values where plain-product had one. The gadget must absorb every one of them, so verifying a sort segment costs more as the segment grows, and the outer circuit grows with it. The measurement shows just this climb: the outer's gate count, fixed for the plain-product inner, rises steadily for the sort inner as $M$ increases. Be honest about the size of the effect, because it is not an explosion. At the largest segments this thesis runs, the sort inner costs the outer a few percent more than the plain-product inner does, no more, and at small segments the gap is nearly nothing. But the _direction_ is the point, and it never turns around: the sort penalty grows with $M$ without bound, while plain-product stays flat at every size. One inner makes the outer answer to the segment's size; the other does not.

So the choice of inner is not free, and recursion forces it. If the outer is to scale, to verify ever-larger segments at a cost that does not run away with them, the inner must publish a _fingerprint_ and not a list, an $O(1)$ surface and not an $O(M)$ one. Plain-product's grand product is exactly that fingerprint, and the forcing is overdetermined: the single field element is at once the surface the measurement rewards and the obvious thing to publish when what you want is a value independent of how many nodes stand behind it. _Plain-product is the inner recursion is forced into._ And that, at last, answers a question the chapter's order has held open since @sec:lever: why build a leaking, plaintext construction at all, only to spend two sections repairing what it gave away? Because the fingerprint that bought almost nothing at the flat level, and only a convenience at the hierarchical one, is the single property the recursive layer cannot do without. Plain-product was never a detour. It was the foundation, introduced where its cost could be read cleanly, before the construction that needed it arrived.

The other candidate rules itself out, for the reason @sub:perfect-hiding already gave. A committed inner would keep the outer flat too, since a commitment is also a single $O(1)$ value; on the cost test it ties plain-product. But it hides values the outer hides anyway, by witnessing them, and pays for the privilege with the commitment machinery inside every segment: a random-oracle wall raised to guard a room the outer has already sealed. So plain-product is forced from both sides, plain-sort priced out by the surface it carries, committed ruled out by the secrecy it duplicates. The plaintext, fingerprint inner is the one the construction wants, and the only one. What that construction costs to run is the last thing the section owes.

#subsection([The Aggregation Tax], label: <sub:aggregation-tax>)

Everything recursion bought, it bought with one expense, and the expense has a clean shape. The outer circuit's cost is dominated by its $K$ in-circuit verifications, each one the price of checking a single proof, which @sub:forced-inner just showed is flat in the segment's size. $K$ verifications, each flat in $M$: so the outer's cost is _$K$-linear and $M$-independent_. It scales with the number of segments, not with how large they are. Cut the tour into more pieces and the aggregation costs proportionally more; make the pieces bigger and it costs the same. Chapter 6 puts the gate counts, the proving times, and the memory to it; the shape is the thing to carry, $K$ up, $M$ flat.

This is the dualism of @sec:dualism in its purest and most punishing form. The dualism said decomposition conserves the prover's total work: what the segments save by being small, the recombination spends to stitch them back together. Every variant has paid it. Recursion pays it hardest. Its glue is no longer a few thousand gates of equality checks and one grand product, the way the plain and committed variants' glue was; it is $K$ full proof verifications carried out inside a circuit, the heaviest recombination the chapter has built. A single one of those verifications already runs on the order of a hundred times the gate count of the entire plain-product glue it stands in for. And recursion does not merely conserve work, shifting it from segment to seam. It piles the largest aggregation cost of any variant on top of inner proofs that are themselves no cheaper than before. Structural hiding, it turns out, is the most expensive thing in the chapter, and it grows dearer with every extra segment.

How far the tax dominates is itself a question of size, and honesty wants the qualification stated plainly. The outer is flat in $M$ where it counts: its $K$ verifications, which are the bulk of it, do not move with the segment, and its only growth with $M$ is the single $O(N)$ coverage product the recombiner still forms once, dwarfed by the verifications. The inner proofs, by contrast, are not flat, growing with the segment exactly as @sub:forced-inner traced. So the two pull apart as $N$ grows. At small instances the $K$ verifications are the bulk of the total work, and the aggregation tax dominates outright. At large instances the inner proofs swell while the outer holds all but flat, so the aggregation becomes a steadily smaller share of a steadily larger whole. The tax is real at every size, but in relative terms it bites hardest exactly where the instances are smallest.

There is a second cost, quieter than the gate count and aimed straight at decomposition's chief prize. Parallelism survives only halfway. The inner segments are still what they always were, small, independent, cheap in memory, each proved on its own machine with no reference to the others. But the outer proof is _one_ proof, and a heavy one: $K$ verifications gathered into a single circuit, whose memory and whose proving time both climb with $K$. So recursion keeps the per-segment parallelism of the inners and gives up the cheap _finish_ the other hierarchical variants enjoyed. Plain-product and committed closed with a light glue proof, a few thousand gates anyone could run in a moment; recursion closes with a single _monolithic_ aggregation that grows with the number of segments. The work in the middle still spreads across machines. The work at the end no longer does.

That monolithic finish is the simplest way to aggregate, not the only one, and the road not taken is worth marking. Folding and tree-recursion schemes, the ClientIVC and Protogalaxy line of work, aggregate proofs incrementally or in pairs rather than all at once in one circuit, so the aggregation itself can be spread across machines the way the segments are. Built on one of those, recursion's finish would parallelize too, and the monolithic step would break apart into a tree. We have not built it. The construction measured here aggregates in a single outer circuit, and the cost we report is that construction's. Folding is the natural resolution of the monolithic finish, named here as future work and claimed as nothing more.

Weigh recursion whole, then, and the chapter's shape comes into view. Recursion bought the privacy endpoint, structural hiding equal to flat's, and a single $O(1)$ verifier, by moving the stitch inside; it paid the steepest cost in the chapter, and it kept only half of decomposition's parallelism, the segments still running apart while the finish stayed monolithic. Set that beside what came before. Flat hid structurally and cost little, but could not be split at all, and ran straight into the wall this chapter began at. Committed split into cheap, fully parallel pieces and cost little, but hid only computationally and disclosed the segment count. No construction holds low cost, full parallelism, and structural hiding at once. Each reaches two of those three only by giving ground on the last, and recursion shows the giving need not even be clean: it surrenders cost outright and keeps no better than a qualified hold on parallelism. That pattern of trades belongs not to any one variant but to the space they share. Mapping it whole, every construction set against every axis, is the work the chapter has left to do, and we turn to it now.

#section([The Frontier], label: <sec:frontier>)

We have built six constructions, the _flat-sort_ baseline of @chap:methodology and the five hierarchical variants of this chapter, and we built them as promised: one at a time, each a single move from the one before. It is time to stop building and look at what we have. Read as a list, the variants are a jumble, five names with tangled, overlapping properties and no clear order among them. Read as a space, they fall into place, because the chapter has been mapping that space all along. Two tools drew it. The _dualism_ of @sec:dualism set one axis: decomposition conserves the prover's total work, so no variant escapes paying for what it stitches, and the only question left is how much each stitch costs. The _stitching tax_ of @sec:stitching-tax set the rest: two decisions, _where_ the stitch lives and _what_ its shared values are made of, with every variant one choice of each. So the constructions are not a list. They are the points of the small space @sec:stitching-tax promised when it had only one corner to show, and every move the chapter made was a step from one point to a neighbour.

Three readings of that space remain, and together they are the chapter's verdict. The first is privacy: what each construction gives away, and on what the secrecy of the rest depends, which sorts the family onto a ladder of three rungs. The second is soundness: what each construction's correctness rests on, the trust it asks a verifier to grant, which is not the same across the family and ought to be said plainly. The third reads privacy, parallelism, and cost together, and it is the finding the whole chapter has been building toward: along the axes that matter, no construction is best, because none holds all of what we want at once. Each buys two of three and gives up the rest. We take the three readings in turn, and the last is where the chapter ends.

#subsection([The Privacy Ladder], label: <sub:privacy-ladder>)

Sort the family by what it hides, and a clean ladder appears, because privacy in this chapter answers to exactly one of the two decisions. @sub:equal-privacy settled which one: not the mechanism, sort or product, which the committed pair proved touches only cost; and not, on its own, the _where_; but the _what_, the substance the shared values are made of. The _what_ has three settings, and they are the ladder's three rungs. Plaintext, a value laid bare. A commitment, a value blinded. Witness, a value never published at all. Each rung hides strictly more than the one beneath it, and every construction sits on the rung its _what_ chooses.

The bottom rung is plaintext, and it does not hide the partition at all. Plain-sort lays the node sets, endpoints, and costs in the clear, and @sec:counting-cost read the whole partition straight off them. Plain-product, the fingerprint lever's work, looks at first like a step up: it publishes one field element where plain-sort published a list. But @sub:product-leak showed the step is an illusion. The product is a confirmation oracle. It does not spell the node set out, but it answers yes or no to any guess, so an adversary recovers the partition by a search, and an adversary who can already guess skips even the search. The lever moved the family _along_ this rung, from a list to a scalar, shrinking the surface and spreading the work; it did not move the family _up_. Plaintext is plaintext, long or short, and the partition on this rung is given away.

The middle rung is the commitment, and it is the first that genuinely hides. @sec:committed wrapped each segment's shared values in a blinded Poseidon fold, and the partition went opaque: behind the commitment a guess has nothing public to check itself against, so the search and the guesser alike are stopped. Both committed variants ride this rung, and @sub:equal-privacy proved they ride it together, equal in what they hide of the partition whichever mechanism did the committing. But the rung's hiding is _computational_: it holds only so long as Poseidon behaves as a random oracle and the blinding stays secret, which @sub:committing-cost priced at one assumption below flat. And one variant carries a little more on its back than the other. Committed-product still publishes its challenge $X$, a fingerprint of the whole ordered cycle; it gives nothing away about the partition, but it is a confirmation oracle one level above, on the full route, that committed-sort, needing no challenge, does without. At the partition the two are level. On the full surface, committed-sort is the quieter by that one whole-cycle handle.

The top rung is witness, and only one construction in the chapter reaches it, by the move the chapter saved for last. To make a shared value witness is to keep it off the public surface entirely, and that cannot be done while the stitch is external, since an external stitch can only compare values that are published. Recursion moved the stitch inside, and with it every shared value off the surface, so the partition is not blinded but _absent_, and @sub:perfect-hiding read the secrecy that follows as structural: resting on nothing flat does not already rest on. This is the rung flat has always stood on, the secrecy @chap:methodology named the _perfect-hiding_ baseline and promised to make precise; _structural_ is that precision, the partition kept off the surface rather than hidden on it. Flat never partitioned, so it never had a partition to hide, and its surface gives nothing away because there is nothing on it to give; recursion partitions, and claws its way back to that same footing by internalizing the stitch. The top rung is shared, then: flat by never dividing, recursion by dividing and then hiding the division completely. That the two arrive together, one having refused decomposition's price and one having paid it in full, is exactly the tension the chapter's last reading turns on.

So privacy is the _what_ axis, clean from bottom to top: plaintext exposes, commitment hides computationally, witness hides structurally. What the ladder does not tell us is whether each construction is _sound_, and on that the family is less uniform than three tidy rungs might suggest. That is the next reading.

#subsection([What Soundness Rests On], label: <sub:soundness-reductions>)

Before sorting the family by what its soundness rests on, it helps to fix what we are leaning on and what we are actually proving. Every construction in this chapter runs on the same proof system, and that system already carries the heaviest guarantee: for whatever circuit we hand it, it certifies, except with negligible probability, that the prover knows a witness satisfying every constraint, and it reveals nothing of that witness beyond the public inputs. We take this as given, citing the proof system's own assumptions rather than reproving them. What is left to us is everything it cannot know on its own: that satisfying _our_ circuit really does imply a sub-threshold Hamiltonian cycle, and that the cryptographic arguments we built _inside_ the circuit — the Merkle openings, the grand product and its challenge, the commitments, the recursive verification — are each sound in their own right. A construction's soundness is therefore a composition rather than a single claim: the proof system's knowledge soundness, assumed; our encoding, that the circuit means what we say; and the in-circuit arguments, each carrying its own small error, the whole no worse than their sum. We only ever add to the proof system's guarantee; we never reach beneath it. This is also why the proof system itself never appears when we tell the constructions apart, here or in the privacy ladder before it: its knowledge soundness and its zero-knowledge are identical under every variant, so whatever separates the constructions is always the layer we built on top.

Privacy sorted the family cleanly because it followed a single decision. Soundness does not, because it follows the other two, and they do not line up with the first. Where the partition's secrecy was set by the _what_, a construction's soundness is set by its _mechanism_, sort or product, and by its _where_, external or internal; the commitment that drove the whole privacy ladder adds only a little. So the variants that were privacy-twins can rest on quite different trust, and the most private need not be the most firmly grounded. Three things carry a hierarchical proof's soundness: the coverage check, the commitment if it has one, and the stitch that ties the proofs together. Take them in turn.

The coverage check splits the family down the mechanism, and it is the sharpest divide in the chapter's soundness. The sort variants check coverage _exactly_: the glue sorts the $N$ published values and reads $0$ through $N - 1$ or does not, an algebraic identity that rests on nothing but field arithmetic and cannot be fooled at any probability. The product variants check coverage _probabilistically_, and @sub:challenge-binding counted the price in full: a grand product is a polynomial identity tested at one challenge, sound only by Schwartz--Zippel, by Fiat--Shamir holding in the random-oracle model, and by Poseidon resisting preimage and collision. The sort variants assume none of that. And notice where the divide falls. Committed-sort and committed-product sat together on the privacy ladder, equal in what they hide; here they part company entirely, the one exact and unconditional in its coverage, the other probabilistic and computational. Privacy twins, soundness strangers. The mechanism the lever chose for reasons of cost turns out to set the coverage's whole trust base, and it does so with no regard for where the construction sits on the privacy ladder.

The commitment adds a second item, and only to the variants that carry one. For the re-fold of @sub:committing to prove anything, the commitment must _bind_: it must open to one set of values and no other, which is Poseidon collision resistance once more. This is a soundness property, not the hiding one, and it is worth seeing what it costs whom. Committed-product was already leaning on collision resistance for its coverage, so binding asks nothing new of it. Committed-sort is the telling case. Its coverage was exact and unconditional, but the moment it commits, its binding rests on a hash, and a sliver of computational assumption enters a construction that had carried none. Committing for privacy, it turns out, quietly draws a soundness assumption along with it, faint but real, and only the sort variant feels the change.

The stitch is the third item, and it is where the _where_ decision finally bears on soundness. The four external variants tie their $K + 1$ proofs with the off-circuit cross-check of @sub:cross-check: a pass of deterministic equality comparisons that assumes nothing cryptographic at all, but lives in trusted verifier _code_, a script that must be written correctly and audited as part of the trust base. Recursion sheds that script entirely, folding the agreement into the outer circuit. But the verification gadget it folds in is not free of trust either: the outer proof's soundness now rests on the recursive proof system itself, on the in-circuit Honk verifier being sound and the recursive composition holding. So the _where_ decision does not remove trust from the stitch; it changes its kind. External pays in auditable, assumption-free code; internal pays in a cryptographic recursion. Neither is nothing, and which a skeptic finds easier to grant is a judgment the construction leaves to them.

Naming the three sources lets us state the claim in the form a reviewer will want: as a _reduction_, not a proof from nothing. We assume the proof system's knowledge soundness and the standard hardness of the primitives, and argue that any successful cheat would have to break one of them. Each construction's knowledge-soundness error $epsilon$ is then no more than the sum of the parts it actually invokes,

$ epsilon <= epsilon_"SNARK" + epsilon_"Merkle" + epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS" + epsilon_"bind" + epsilon_"rec" , $

with $epsilon_"SNARK"$ the proof system's own assumed error; $epsilon_"Merkle"$ the chance a Poseidon2 collision opens a wrong matrix cell; $epsilon_"SZ" <= N\/|FF|$ the Schwartz--Zippel failure of the grand product; $epsilon_"FS"$ the error of deriving the challenge by Fiat--Shamir in the random-oracle model; $epsilon_"bind"$ the commitment's binding error, a Poseidon2 collision once more; and $epsilon_"rec"$ the recursive verifier's soundness error. The external cross-check contributes no term of its own: its equality comparisons are deterministic, so they add audited code to the trust base but no probability of failure — which is why a leaking external stitch costs nothing in $epsilon$ over the flat proof. Every variant shares the first two terms; which of the rest it carries is exactly its trust base, and they are few (@tab:soundness-terms).

#figure(
  caption: [Each construction's knowledge-soundness trust base, written as the error terms it adds _beyond_ the two every variant shares: $epsilon_"SNARK"$ (the proof system) and $epsilon_"Merkle"$ (the matrix binding). Only the product and recursive variants invoke the random-oracle model.],
  table(
    columns: (auto, 1fr, auto),
    align: (left, left, center),
    table.header([*variant*], [*added error terms*], [*ROM?*]),
    [flat-sort], [--- (exact coverage, monolithic)], [no],
    [plain-sort], [--- (exact coverage; external stitch adds code, not error)], [no],
    [plain-product], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS"$], [yes],
    [committed-sort], [$epsilon_"bind"$], [no],
    [committed-product], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS" + epsilon_"bind"$], [yes],
    [recursion], [$epsilon_"SZ" + epsilon_"FS" + epsilon_"rec"$], [yes],
  ),
) <tab:soundness-terms>

So three of the family reduce end to end without ever invoking the random-oracle model: flat-sort, plain-sort, and committed-sort rest only on the proof system, Poseidon2 collision resistance, and — for the last — its binding. The product and recursive variants carry, in addition, the Fiat--Shamir argument in the random-oracle model, and recursion the soundness of recursive composition on top; these we state as reductions to cited results, not as fresh proofs. And we are explicit about what we do _not_ claim: a random-oracle-free analysis of Fiat--Shamir, a machine-checked proof, or formal verification of the Noir circuits themselves. Each is a real limitation, named here and taken up again in the conclusion.

Lay the trust bases side by side and soundness is plainly not a ladder but a spread, one that runs across the privacy order rather than along it. The lightest base among the hierarchical family belongs to plain-sort: exact coverage, no commitment, and a stitch of plain equality checks; lighter still, with no stitch to trust at all, is the flat proof it descends from. But plain-sort hides nothing. The most private construction, recursion, carries one of the heaviest bases instead: probabilistic coverage, because @sub:forced-inner forced a product inner upon it, and a recursive verification stacked on top. So the exactness the sort offers and the structural hiding the recursion offers sit at opposite ends of the family, and in the efficient constructions they cannot be had together: choose exact coverage and the best privacy within reach is computational; choose structural privacy and the coverage beneath it is probabilistic. One could in principle recurse on a sort inner and hold both at once, but @sub:forced-inner already measured what that costs, an outer that swells with the segment. Soundness, like everything else in this chapter, trades. What it trades against cost, and how the whole of it nets out, is the last reading, and we turn to it now.

#subsection([Pick Two], label: <sub:pick-two>)

The last reading is cost, and with it the three come together. We have read what each construction hides and what its soundness rests on; the dualism gave us the third axis at the very start, that decomposition conserves the prover's work and the only question is how dearly each variant pays to recombine. Put the three side by side and the practical question finally has an answer, though not the kind one hopes for. Ask which construction is best and the honest reply is that none is, because the three things we want from a hierarchical proof pull against one another. We want it _cheap_, costing no more than the work decomposition cannot avoid. We want it _parallel_, its work spread across machines so that the wall of @sec:dualism stays cleared. And we want it _structurally private_, the partition hidden the way flat hides it, on no assumption. No construction in the chapter holds all three.

Each holds two and gives up the third, and which it gives up names it. Flat is cheap and structurally private, and it cannot be split at all: it is the corner that runs into the wall this chapter began at, the reason we ever decomposed. Committed is cheap and fully parallel, segments and finish alike spread thin, and its privacy is only computational, a wall of assumption thrown up around a partition still sitting on the surface. Recursion is structurally private and parallel, and it is the most expensive construction in the chapter, its aggregation tax climbing with every segment. Three goods, three corners, and one shape behind them: you may pick two. Cheap and private costs you parallelism; cheap and parallel costs you structural privacy; private and parallel costs you the aggregation tax. The pick-two triangle is the chapter's central finding, and it is a property not of any one construction but of the space they share.

Recursion's corner is the roughest of the three, and honesty asks that we say so rather than round it off. Its hold on parallelism is real but partial. The segments parallelize as cleanly as any variant's, but the finish does not: the aggregation is one monolithic proof, and the very tax that makes recursion the most expensive corner falls precisely on that un-parallel finish. So recursion does not sit at its corner as easily as committed sits at its own. It keeps parallelism in the segments and surrenders it at the end, and pays the steepest price of all for the privacy it holds. Folding, named in @sub:aggregation-tax and not built, is the one move that would smooth this corner, breaking the monolithic finish into a parallel tree. Until it is built, recursion's structural privacy carries both the highest cost in the family and a finish that stands alone.

One thing the triangle leaves out, and the omission is the point. The plain variants are nowhere on it. Plaintext hides nothing, so plain-sort and plain-product are cheap and parallel but private in no sense at all; committed reaches the same cost and the same parallelism and adds computational privacy on top, for the small fixed price @sub:committing-cost weighed. Committed _dominates_ plain on the three axes the triangle measures: there is no reason to deploy a plain variant where a committed one costs almost the same and hides far more. So the deployable frontier is three points, not five, flat and committed and recursion. The plain constructions were never destinations. They were the rungs we climbed to reach the others, and one of them, plain-product, the substrate @sub:forced-inner showed recursion could not be built without. We built them leaking, out in the open, because building them so was the honest way to see, one decision at a time, what each later move bought.

So the chapter closes where its first section pointed. We asked whether a proof of a route could be cut into independent pieces and still hide the route, and whether cutting it would ever cost less than proving it whole. The dualism answered the second question first, and answered it no: there is no size at which decomposition is cheaper, no crossover, only work relocated and a tax for relocating it. What remained was not a winner to crown but a space to map, and the map is the pick-two triangle. A carrier who must prove her route under budget without revealing it now chooses not the best construction but the sacrifice she can afford: the wall, if her instances are small enough to prove whole; computational privacy, if she needs them cheap and parallel; or the aggregation tax, if she needs the route hidden on no assumption and her instances proved in pieces. The contribution of this chapter is that map, and the understanding, earned one construction at a time, of why it takes the shape it does. The numbers that pin each corner to the axis it pays are the work of Chapter 6.
